<p><b>Short bowel syndrome</b> (<b>SBS</b>, also <b>short gut syndrome</b> or simply <b>short gut</b>) is a <a href="/wiki/Malabsorption" title="Malabsorption">malabsorption</a> disorder caused by the <a href="/wiki/Surgery" title="Surgery">surgical</a> removal of the <a href="/wiki/Small_intestine" title="Small intestine">small intestine</a>, or rarely due to the complete dysfunction of a large segment of bowel. Most cases are acquired, although some children are born with a congenital short bowel. It usually does not develop unless more than two thirds of the small intestine have been removed. SBS has been designated a <a href="/wiki/Rare_disease" title="Rare disease">rare disease</a> by the <a href="/wiki/European_Medicines_Agency" title="European Medicines Agency">EMA</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-orphanet104008_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-orphanet104008-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> and is eligible for <a href="/wiki/Orphan_drug" title="Orphan drug">orphan drug</a> designation according to the U.S. <a href="/wiki/Food_and_Drug_Administration" title="Food and Drug Administration">Food and Drug Administration</a> (FDA).<sup id="cite_ref-teduglutideFDA_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-teduglutideFDA-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> There are roughly 3,500 adults and 9,000 children with SBS in the USA alone.</p>
<p></p>
<div id="toc" class="toc">
